In this posting:
[1] Krasnodar
[2] Rostov

******
[1] Krasnodar
Date: Tue 17 Aug 2010
Source: New Izvestia [in Russian, trans. Corr.ATS, edited]
<http://www.newizv.ru/lenta/131592/>


Outbreak of African swine fever in Krasnodar territory
-------------------------------------------------------
An outbreak of African swine fever (ASF) has been registered in the
Severskoy rayon [district] of Krasnodar krai [territory].

The office of the regional Rosselkhoznadzor [Federal Service for
Veterinary and Phytosanitary Surveillance] reported that 2 carcasses
of wild boars were found in the forest near Solenaya Shel. The
veterinary tests confirmed that the boars died from ASF. Quarantine
measures were imposed in the surrounding territories to avoid the
spread of ASF. There have been 3 outbreaks of ASF in Krasnodar krai
since the beginning of 2010.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-RUS
<promed-rus@promedmail.org>

******
[2] Rostov
Date: Sun 22 Aug 2010
Source: Komsomolskaya Pravda [in Russian, trans. Corr.ATS, edited]
<http://rostov.kp.ru/online/news/724906/>


14 000 pigs destroyed in the Rostov region due to African swine fever
------------------------------------------------------------
New ASF outbreaks were registered in Rostov oblast [region].
Particularly, it was decided to apply emergency measures in
Martinovski rayon after the laboratory tests confirmed that ASF virus
is present in the bones of dead wild swine, found near Komarovski village.

ASF outbreaks appeared simultaneously in 2 villages of Ust-Donetsk
rayon. The swine population of the large farm "Russkaya svinya"
("Russian pork") has also been affected. As of 19 Aug 2010, 1200 pigs
died or were destroyed there because of ASF. It was decided to cull
all 14 500 pigs in this particular farm.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-RUS
<promed-rus@promedmail.org>

[Russia's last follow-up report concerning ASF was submitted to the
OIE on 10 Aug 2010; in case the current additional information above
is confirmed, this information, in detail, is expected to be included
in a due new follow-up report. All 38 follow-up reports, covering the
81 ASF outbreaks in Russia since 11 Sep 2009, including an
interactive map (zoom in!), are available at
<http://www.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=event_summary&reportid=8462>.
- Mod.AS]
